# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Amasa Learned (Pro-Administration) was elected September 19, 1791 in Connecticut's at-large congressional district to finish the term of Roger Sherman (Pro-Administration).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election] Sherman had been re-elected in 1790, but resigned June 13, 1791 to become U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] Learned was born in Killingly in the Connecticut Colony, the son of Deacon Ebenezer Learned and Keziah (Leavens) Learned.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] He was prepared for college by a private tutor and graduated from Yale College in 1772.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] Learned taught in the Union School in New London.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] He studied theology, received a license from the Windham Association in October 1773, and preached for a short time before entering politics.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] While living in Killingly, Learned began the study of law in 1778.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] He was elected a member of the Connecticut House of Representatives in 1779.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] After moving to New London, he served again in the Connecticut House of Representatives from 1785 to 1791.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] He was a member of the convention which ratified the Constitution of the United States in 1788.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] Learned was elected to the upper house of assistants in 1791, and simultaneously served as a judge of the Connecticut Supreme Court of Errors from 1791 to 1792.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] He was elected as a Pro-Administration candidate to the Second and Third Congresses, serving from March 4, 1791, to March 3, 1795; he was also the runner-up for another of Connecticut's at-large congressional districts in a December 1790 special election, losing to Jeremiah Wadsworth.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] He engaged in land speculations while serving in Congress.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] After serving in Congress, he was a delegate to the state constitutional convention in 1818.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] His grandsons were Connecticut politician William Henry Law and U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/amasa-learned] Learned died in New London on May 4, 1825.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state is named after the Connecticut River, the longest in New England, which roughly bisects the state and drains into the Long Island Sound between the towns of Old Saybrook and Old Lyme.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The name of the river is in turn derived from anglicized spellings of *Quinnetuket*, a Mohegan-Pequot word for "long tidal river".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Before the arrival of the first European settlers, the region was inhabited by various Algonquian tribes.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1633, the Dutch West India Company established a small, short-lived settlement called House of Hope in Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Half of Connecticut was initially claimed by the Dutch colony New Netherland, which included much of the land between the Connecticut and Delaware Rivers, although the first major settlements were established by the English around the same time.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Thomas Hooker led a band of followers from the Massachusetts Bay Colony to form the Connecticut Colony, while other settlers from Massachusetts founded the Saybrook Colony and the New Haven Colony; both had merged into the first by 1664.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's environmental history is shaped by Indigenous land stewardship, colonial displacement, industrial development, and modern environmental regulation.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Pequot and Mohegan peoples maintained sustainable relationships with the land prior to colonization, which were later disrupted by forced removal and legal restrictions on land and sovereignty.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Industrial growth in the 19th and 20th centuries concentrated manufacturing along river systems, contributing to pollution and environmental inequality.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In response, modern state and federal environmental policies have been developed to regulate pollution and protect natural resources.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's official nickname, the "Constitution State", refers to the Fundamental Orders adopted by the Connecticut Colony in 1639, which is considered by some to be the first written constitution in Western history.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] As one of the Thirteen Colonies that rejected British rule during the American Revolution, Connecticut was influential in the development of the federal government of the United States.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In January 1788, Connecticut became the fifth state to ratify the Constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut is a developed and affluent state, performing well on the Human Development Index and on different metrics of income except for equality.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] It is home to a number of prestigious educational institutions, including Yale University in New Haven, as well as other liberal arts colleges and private boarding schools in and around the "Knowledge Corridor".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Due to its geography, Connecticut has maintained a strong maritime tradition; the United States Coast Guard Academy is located in New London by the Thames River.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state is also associated with the aerospace industry through major companies Pratt & Whitney and Sikorsky Aircraft headquartered in East Hartford and Stratford, respectively.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The name of this state, *Connecticut*, is derived from the Mohegan-Pequot word that has been translated as "long tidal river" and "upon the long river", both referring to the Connecticut River.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Evidence of human presence in the Connecticut region dates to as far back as 10,000 years ago.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Stone tools were used for hunting, fishing, and woodworking.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Semi-nomadic in lifestyle, these peoples moved seasonally to take advantage of various resources in the area.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] They shared languages based on Algonquian.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Connecticut region was inhabited by many Native American tribes that can be grouped into the Nipmuc, the Sequin or "River Indians" (which included the Tunxis, Schaghticoke, Podunk, Wangunk, Hammonasset, and Quinnipiac), the Mattabesec or "Wappinger Confederacy" and the Pequot-Mohegan.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Some of these groups still reside in Connecticut, including the Mohegans, the Pequots, and the Paugusetts.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In the seventeenth century, more than 8,000 Pequots lived in the Western part of Connecticut into Rhode Island, while 1,500 to 2,500 Mohegans resided West of the Thames River.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Mohegans lived on traditions like hunting, shell fishing, gathering and maize agriculture.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This system was passed down through intergenerational knowledge and traditions.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Cultural continuity was maintained through oral traditions, which functioned as both historical record and ecological knowledge system.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This preserved relationships between people, land, and nonhuman life, while also preserving and acknowledging the past.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] An important relationship the Mohegans preserved was one also similar to the Lenape Nation, and that was the Three Sisters Mound.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This consisted of corn, beans, and squash, and it nourished the Mohegan tribe throughout the whole year.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Mohegan people used polycultural methods of agriculture that reinforced their relations with the land.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Mohegan elder Gladys Tantaquidgeon said, “We hold in reverence the Spirit of Corn,” which reflected the idea that food systems were inseparable from Mohegan culture.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Pequot and Mohegan tribes practiced rituals like controlled burns, sustainable fishing techniques, and seasonal migration.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This reflected their idea that humans were a part of the natural world, not superior to it.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Such approaches exemplify environmental management and highlight a worldview centered on balance, responsibility, and reciprocal relationships between humans and the natural world.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This deep connection to and reliance on the natural environment is also evident in their cultural and economic traditions, particularly in the use of wampum.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Wampum, created from a quahog or whelk shell, was often exchanged at weddings, as a gift, or to symbolize an agreement or deal between two groups of people.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Beyond being an economically functioning object, the wampum represented promise, honor, and truth within the Native Nations of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] It is sourced from the Thames River, which signifies the importance of land and its parts to the Mohegan tribe.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Mohegan and Pequot societies depended on the river and living organisms within it to structure their society, and the wampum is another example of environmental interdependence within Connecticut Native Nations.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Dutchman Adriaen Block was the first European explorer in Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Dutch fur traders then sailed up the Connecticut River, calling it Versche Rivier ("Fresh River") and building a fort at Dutch Point in Hartford, which they named "House of Hope" (Dutch: *Huis van Hoop*).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Connecticut Colony originally consisted of several smaller settlements in Windsor, Wethersfield, Saybrook, Hartford, and New Haven.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The first English settlers came in 1633 and settled at Windsor, then at Wethersfield the following year.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] John Winthrop the Younger of Massachusetts received a commission to create Saybrook Colony at the mouth of the Connecticut River in 1635.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] A large group of Puritans arrived in 1636 from Massachusetts Bay Colony, led by Thomas Hooker, who established the Connecticut Colony at Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Fundamental Orders of Connecticut were adopted in January 1639, and have been described as the first constitutional document in America.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Quinnipiack Colony was established by John Davenport, Theophilus Eaton, and others at New Haven in March 1638.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The New Haven Colony had its own constitution called "The Fundamental Agreement of the New Haven Colony", signed on June 4, 1639.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Each settlement was an independent political entity, established without official sanction of the English Crown.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1662, Winthrop traveled to England and obtained a charter from Charles II which united the settlements of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Pequot War marked the first significant clash between colonists and Native Americans in New England.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Pequot had been aggressively extending their area of control at the expense of the Wampanoag to the north, Narragansett (east), Connecticut River Valley Algonquian tribes and the Mohegan (west), and Lenape Algonquian people (south).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Meanwhile, the Pequot had been reacting with increasing aggression to colonial territorial expansion.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In response to the 1636 murder of an English privateer and his crew, followed by the murder of a trader, colonists raided a Pequot village on Block Island.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Pequots laid siege to Saybrook Colony's garrison that autumn, then raided Wethersfield in the spring of 1637.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Organizing a band of militia and allies from the Mohegan and Narragansett tribes, colonists declared war and attacked a Pequot village on the Mystic River.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Death toll estimates range between 300 and 700 Pequots.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] After suffering another major loss at a battle in Fairfield, the Pequots sued for peace.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Mashantucket Pequot Nation, descendants of the Pequot people of southern New England, experienced significant population loss due to violence and disease in the early seventeenth century.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In the aftermath, Pequot leaders sued for peace, resulting in the Treaty of Hartford, which divided the surviving Pequots among the Narragansett and Mohegan tribes and forbade them from being called “Pequot” or returning to their homeland.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Pequots and Mohegan tribes assimilated to many European cultural practices.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This erased generations of knowledge and tradition.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Not until 1651 were the Pequots able to gather the rights to resettle on 500 acres of their original ancestral land.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] During the 18th and 19th centuries, the Pequots and Mohegans were forcefully removed from ancestral lands.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The societal structures of these Native Nations dictate their relationship with land.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] As Vanessa Watts says, they believe that their "land is alive and thinking, humans and nonhumans derive agency through extension of these thoughts".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The displacement of Native Americans from their land severed these relationships, which undermines their systems of knowledge, identity, and ultimately their culture.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In more recent years, the restoration of Mohegan lands and cultural practices has faced legal and historical challenges.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This is due to the Mohegan Land case, where colonists argued that colonial land could not be given back to native tribes because it was already ‘colonial in nature’, and would be turned back to ‘wilderness’, if put in native possession again.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] As reflected in disputes over the 1681 treaty, colonial officials asserted full ownership of lands while simultaneously documenting them as part of Native territory, enabling the continued sale and settlement of those lands without consent from the Mohegan Tribe.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] While the Pequot Tribe sought to maintain and regain their land, colonial and later American legal frameworks often created obstacles to the full recovery of ancestral territories.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's original Charter in 1662 granted it all the land to the "South Sea"—that is, to the Pacific Ocean.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Hartford Treaty with the Dutch was signed on September 19, 1650, but never ratified by the British, stated the western boundary of Connecticut ran north from Greenwich Bay for a distance of 20 miles (32 km), "provided the said line come not within 10 miles [16 km] of Hudson River".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This agreement was observed by both sides until war erupted between England and The Netherlands in 1652.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Conflict continued concerning colonial limits until the Duke of York captured New Netherland in 1664.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Most Colonial royal grants were for long east–west strips.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut took its grant seriously and established a ninth county between the Susquehanna River and Delaware River named Westmoreland County.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This resulted in the brief Pennamite-Yankee Wars with Pennsylvania.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Yale College was established in 1701, providing Connecticut with an important institution to educate clergy and civil leaders.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Congregational church dominated religious life in the colony and, by extension, town affairs in many parts.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] With more than 600 miles (970 km) of coastline including along its navigable rivers, Connecticut developed the antecedents of a maritime tradition during its colonial years that would later produce booms in shipbuilding, marine transport, naval support, seafood production, and leisure boating.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Historical records list the *Tryall* as the first vessel built in Connecticut Colony, in 1649 at a site on the Connecticut River in modern Wethersfield.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's first lighthouse was constructed in 1760 at the mouth of the Thames River with the New London Harbor Lighthouse.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut designated four delegates to the Second Continental Congress who signed the Declaration of Independence: Samuel Huntington, Roger Sherman, William Williams, and Oliver Wolcott.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's legislature authorized the outfitting of six new regiments in 1775, in the wake of the clashes between British regulars and Massachusetts militia at Lexington and Concord.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] There were some 1,200 Connecticut troops on hand at the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1775, David Bushnell invented the *Turtle* which the following year launched the first submarine attack in history, unsuccessfully against a British warship at anchor in New York Harbor.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1777, the British got word of Continental Army supplies in Danbury, and they landed an expeditionary force of some 2,000 troops in Westport.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This force marched to Danbury, then destroyed homes and much of the depot.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Continental Army troops and militia led by General David Wooster and General Benedict Arnold engaged them on their return march at Ridgefield in 1777.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] For the winter of 1778–79, General George Washington decided to split the Continental Army into three divisions encircling New York City, where British General Sir Henry Clinton had taken up winter quarters.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Major General Israel Putnam chose Redding as the winter encampment quarters for some 3,000 regulars and militia under his command.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Redding encampment allowed Putnam's soldiers to guard the replenished supply depot in Danbury and to support any operations along Long Island Sound and the Hudson River Valley.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Some of the men were veterans of the winter encampment at Valley Forge, Pennsylvania, the previous winter.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Soldiers at the Redding camp endured supply shortages, cold temperatures, and significant snow, with some historians dubbing the encampment "Connecticut's Valley Forge".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state was also the launching site for a number of raids against Long Island orchestrated by Samuel Holden Parsons and Benjamin Tallmadge, and provided soldiers and material for the war effort, especially to Washington's army outside New York City.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] General William Tryon raided the Connecticut coast in July 1779, focusing on New Haven, Norwalk, and Fairfield.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] New London and Groton Heights were raided in September 1781 by Benedict Arnold, who had turned traitor to the British.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Constitution on January 9, 1788, becoming the fifth state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state prospered during the era following the American Revolution, as mills and textile factories were built and seaports flourished from trade and fisheries.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] After Congress established in 1790 the predecessor to the U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Revenue Cutter Service that would evolve into the U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Coast Guard, President Washington assigned Jonathan Maltbie as one of seven masters to enforce customs regulations, with Maltbie monitoring the southern New England coast with a 48-foot cutter sloop named *Argus*.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1786, Connecticut ceded territory to the U.S. government that became part of the Northwest Territory.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state retained land extending across the northern part of modern Ohio called the Connecticut Western Reserve.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Western Reserve section was settled largely by people from Connecticut, and they brought Connecticut place names to Ohio.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut made agreements with Pennsylvania and New York which extinguished the land claims within those states' boundaries and created the Connecticut Panhandle.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state then ceded the Western Reserve in 1800 to the federal government, which brought it to its existing boundaries (other than minor adjustments with Massachusetts).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] For the first time in 1800, Connecticut shipwrights launched more than 100 vessels in a single year.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Over the following decade up to the doorstep of renewed hostilities with Britain that sparked the War of 1812, Connecticut boatyards constructed close to 1,000 vessels, the most productive stretch of any decade in the nineteenth century.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] During the war, the British launched raids in Stonington and Essex and blockaded vessels in the Thames River.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Derby native Isaac Hull became Connecticut's best-known naval figure to win renown during the conflict, as captain of the USS *Constitution*.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The British blockade during the War of 1812 hurt exports and bolstered the influence of Federalists who opposed the war.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The cessation of imports from Britain stimulated the construction of factories to manufacture textiles and machinery.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut came to be recognized as a major center for manufacturing, due in part to the inventions of Eli Whitney and other early innovators of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The war led to the development of fast clippers that helped extend the reach of New England merchants to the Pacific and Indian oceans.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The first half of the nineteenth century saw as well a rapid rise in whaling, with New London emerging as one of the New England industry's three biggest home ports after Nantucket and New Bedford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state was known for its political conservatism, typified by its Federalist party and the Yale College of Timothy Dwight.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The foremost intellectuals were Dwight and Noah Webster, who compiled his great dictionary in New Haven.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Religious tensions polarized the state, as the Congregational Church struggled to maintain traditional viewpoints, in alliance with the Federalists.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The failure of the Hartford Convention in 1814 hurt the Federalist cause, with the Democratic-Republican Party gaining control in 1817.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut had been governed under the "Fundamental Orders" since 1639, but the state adopted a new constitution in 1818.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut manufacturers played a major role in supplying the Union forces with weapons and supplies during the Civil War.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state furnished 55,000 men, formed into thirty full regiments of infantry, including two in the U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Colored Troops, with several Connecticut men becoming generals.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Navy attracted 250 officers and 2,100 men, and Glastonbury native Gideon Welles was Secretary of the Navy.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut casualties included 2,088 killed in combat, 2,801 dying from disease, and 689 dying in Confederate prison camps.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] A surge of national unity in 1861 brought thousands flocking to the colors from every town and city.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] However, as the war became a crusade to end slavery, many Democrats (especially Irish Catholics) pulled back.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Democrats took a pro-slavery position and included many Copperheads willing to let the South secede.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The intensely fought 1863 election for governor was narrowly won by the Republicans.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Jewett City, which is modern day Griswold Connecticut, is one of the original examples of industrial development in Connecticut within the nineteenth century.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Samuel Slater started the expansion of textile and cotton manufacturing into Connecticut starting in 1823.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] These manufacturing systems relied heavily on the two main rivers within the region: the Pachaug and the Quinebaug.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The running water from these rivers powered textile mills and factories all along that region of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] These factories relied on running water to turn belt systems using turbines.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The construction of these dams and turbines changed the river flow, which prevented fish from migrating up and down rivers, and also flooded the surrounding wetlands.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] As time went on, the rivers became increasingly more polluted.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Millions of gallons of waste water were dumped into the waterways, which often combined with municipal sewage.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] During this time, the only source of freshwater was from nearby streams and rivers.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This polluted the local drinking water and had a severe effect on the surrounding population.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Mills were often located next to low income, marginalized communities.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This can be seen within the city of Danbury, as mills were located along the Still and Housatonic Rivers.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Elemental mercury, copper, zinc, and lead was deposited as wastewater into these freshwater streams.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Economic necessity drove citizens to these jobs despite the environmental and health risks.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] By 1887, there were 30 hat factories across the city.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] However, by 1923, only six were left within the city.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The hat industry was the primary source of employment in places like Danbury, where the economy depended heavily on hat manufacturing; as factories closed due to changing fashions and economic downturns, this led to reduced employment opportunities and economic instability in the community.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Similar issues also happened in Jewett City, as it was located next to the two largest Native American reservations within the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's extensive industry, dense population, flat terrain, and wealth encouraged the construction of railroads starting in 1839.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The New York, New Haven and Hartford Railroad, called the *New Haven* or "The Consolidated", became the dominant Connecticut railroad company after 1872.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Morgan began financing the major New England railroads in the 1890s, dividing territory so that they would not compete.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The New Haven purchased 50 smaller companies, including steamship lines, and built a network of light rails (electrified trolleys) that provided inter-urban transportation for all of southern New England.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] By 1912, the New Haven operated over 2,000 miles (3,200 km) of track with 120,000 employees.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] As steam-powered passenger ships proliferated after the Civil War, Noank produced the two largest built in Connecticut during the nineteenth century, with the 332-foot wooden steam paddle wheeler *Rhode Island* launched in 1882, and the 345-foot paddle wheeler *Connecticut* seven years later.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut shipyards launched more than 165 steam-powered vessels in the nineteenth century.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1875, the first telephone exchange in the world was established in New Haven.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] When World War I broke out in 1914, Connecticut became a major supplier of weaponry to the U.S. military; by 1918, 80% of the state's industries were producing goods for the war effort.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Remington Arms in Bridgeport produced half the small-arms cartridges used by the U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Army, with other major suppliers including Winchester in New Haven and Colt in Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Navy supplier, with Electric Boat receiving orders for 85 submarines, Lake Torpedo Boat building more than 20 subs, and the Groton Iron Works building freighters.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] On June 21, 1916, the Navy made Groton the site for its East Coast submarine base and school.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state enthusiastically supported the American war effort in 1917 and 1918 with large purchases of war bonds, a further expansion of industry, and an emphasis on increasing food production on the farms.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Thousands of state, local, and volunteer groups mobilized for the war effort and were coordinated by the Connecticut State Council of Defense.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Manufacturers wrestled with manpower shortages; Waterbury's American Brass and Manufacturing Company was running at half capacity, so the federal government agreed to furlough soldiers to work there.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Henry Roraback started the Connecticut Light & Power Co. which became the state's dominant electric utility.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1925, Frederick Rentschler spurred the creation of Pratt & Whitney in Hartford to develop engines for aircraft; the company became an important military supplier in World War II and one of the three major manufacturers of jet engines in the world.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] On September 21, 1938, the most destructive storm in New England history struck eastern Connecticut, killing hundreds of people.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The eye of the "Long Island Express" passed just west of New Haven and devastated the Connecticut shoreline between Old Saybrook and Stonington from the full force of wind and waves, even though they had partial protection by Long Island.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The hurricane caused extensive damage to infrastructure, homes, and businesses.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In New London, a 500-foot (150 m) sailing ship was driven into a warehouse complex, causing a major fire.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Heavy rainfall caused the Connecticut River to flood downtown Hartford and East Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] An estimated 50,000 trees fell onto roadways.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The advent of lend-lease in support of Britain helped lift Connecticut from the Great Depression, with the state a major production center for weaponry and supplies used in World War II.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] On May 13, 1940, Igor Sikorsky made an untethered flight of the first practical helicopter.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The helicopter saw limited use in World War II, but future military production made Sikorsky Aircraft's Stratford plant Connecticut's largest single manufacturing site by the start of the twenty-first century.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut was known as the “Provisions State” or the “Arsenal of Democracy” during wartime for its production efforts during the Revolutionary, Civil, and World Wars.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state quickly transformed into a manufacturing powerhouse.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] With its strong history of aircraft and manufacturing, Connecticut was a large part of the World War II home front.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Pratt & Whitney was a large Connecticut run manufacturing company, and by 1943, 96% of all U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Army and Navy transport planes used Pratt & Whitney engines.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state also produced ammunition, auto parts, and airplanes.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] While this allowed for the state to amass a large amount of revenue, it also caused severe environmental and economic issues once the war ended.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] For example, the US Naval base in New London, CT allowed for many industrial level pollutants to enter Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Items like acid-filled ship batteries, oil, and petroleum were shipped to help fuel the war grade submarines.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The EPA has ordered tests and studies that identified “polyaromatic hydrocarbons, or PAHs; polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs; lead, metals and pesticides” present within the bases surroundings.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] These pollutants are hard to break down, and cause cancer, development issues, damage to the nervous system, disruption of cognitive function.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This disrupts not only the food chain and the biodiversity of the area, but the civilians local to the base are put in harm's way.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This did not just happen due to the Naval presence in Connecticut, but was also due to the large scale manufacturing and agricultural upticks occurring within the state during World War II.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut lost some wartime factories following the end of hostilities, but the state shared in a general post-war expansion that included the construction of highways and resulting in middle-class growth in suburban areas.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Prescott Bush represented Connecticut in the U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Senate from 1952 to 1963; his son George H.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Bush both became presidents of the United States.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1965, Connecticut ratified its current constitution, replacing the document that had served since 1818.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1968, commercial operation began for the Connecticut Yankee Nuclear Power Plant in Haddam; in 1970, the Millstone Nuclear Power Station began operations in Waterford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1974, Connecticut elected Democratic Governor Ella T.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Grasso, who became the first woman in any state to be elected governor without being the wife or widow of a previous governor.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The postwar period also brought economic decline, as industrial jobs rapidly disappeared.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] 10,200 employees in Waterbury factories were let go within a week of V-J Day.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] At the same time, environmental degradation remained, with waterways contaminated by industrial byproducts such as heavy metals, dyes, and pesticides.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Most of Connecticut's wetlands had been destroyed by development, which reduces the ecological resilience of the area.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's dependence on the defense industry posed an economic challenge at the end of the Cold War.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The resulting budget crisis helped elect Lowell Weicker as governor on a third-party ticket in 1990.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Weicker's remedy was a state income tax which proved effective in balancing the budget, but only for the short-term.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] He did not run for a second term, in part because of this politically unpopular move.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 1992, initial construction was completed on Foxwoods Casino at the Mashantucket Pequots reservation in eastern Connecticut, which became the largest casino in the Western Hemisphere.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In 2000, presidential candidate Al Gore chose Senator Joe Lieberman as his running mate, marking the first time that a major party presidential ticket included someone of the Jewish faith.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Gore and Lieberman fell five votes short of George W.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Bush and Dick Cheney in the Electoral College.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, 65 state residents were killed, mostly Fairfield County residents who were working in the World Trade Center.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Rowland resigned during a corruption investigation, later pleading guilty to federal charges.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut was hit by three major storms in just over 14 months in 2011 and 2012, with all three causing extensive property damage and electric outages.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Hurricane Irene struck Connecticut August 28, and damage totaled $235 million.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Two months later, the "Halloween nor'easter" dropped extensive snow onto trees, resulting in snapped branches and trunks that damaged power lines; some areas were without electricity for 11 days.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Hurricane Sandy hit New Jersey and passed over Connecticut with hurricane-force winds and tides up to 12 feet above normal.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Many coastal buildings were damaged or destroyed.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Sandy's winds drove storm surges into streets and cut power to 98% of homes and businesses, with more than $360 million in damage.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] On December 14, 2012, a 20-year-old man named Adam Lanza shot and killed 26 people at Sandy Hook Elementary School in Newtown, and then killed himself.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The massacre spurred renewed efforts by activists for tighter laws on gun ownership nationally.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] In the summer and fall of 2016, Connecticut experienced a drought in many parts of the state, causing some water-use bans.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] As of November 15, 2016 (2016-11-15), 45% of the state was listed at Severe Drought by the U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Drought Monitor, including almost all of Hartford and Litchfield counties.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] All the rest of the state was in Moderate Drought or Severe Drought, including Middlesex, Fairfield, New London, New Haven, Windham, and Tolland counties.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] This affected the agricultural economy in the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut is bordered on the south by Long Island Sound, on the west by New York, on the north by Massachusetts, and on the east by Rhode Island.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state's capital and fourth-largest city is Hartford, and other major cities and towns (by population) include Bridgeport, New Haven, Stamford, Waterbury, Norwalk, Danbury, New Britain, Greenwich, and Bristol.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] There are 169 incorporated towns in Connecticut, with cities and villages included within some towns.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The highest peak in Connecticut is Bear Mountain in Salisbury in the northwest corner of the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The highest point is just east of where Connecticut, Massachusetts, and New York meet (42°3′ N, 73°29′ W), on the southern slope of Mount Frissell, whose peak lies nearby in Massachusetts.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] At the opposite extreme, many of the coastal towns have areas that are less than 20 feet (6.1 m) above sea level.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut has a long maritime history and a reputation based on that history—yet the state has no direct oceanfront (technically speaking).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The coast of Connecticut sits on Long Island Sound, which is an estuary.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The state's access to the open Atlantic Ocean is both to the west (toward New York City) and to the east (toward the "race" near Rhode Island).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Due to this unique geography, Long Island Sound and the Connecticut shoreline are relatively protected from high waves from storms.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The Connecticut River cuts through the center of the state, flowing into Long Island Sound.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The most populous metropolitan region centered within the state lies in the Connecticut River Valley.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Many towns in northeastern and northwestern Connecticut center around a green.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Near the green typically stand historical visual symbols of New England towns, such as a white church, a colonial meeting house, a colonial tavern or inn, several colonial houses, and so on, establishing a scenic historical appearance maintained for both historic preservation and tourism.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Many of the areas in southern and coastal Connecticut have been built up and rebuilt over the years, and look less visually like traditional New England.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The northern boundary of the state with Massachusetts is marked by the Southwick Jog or Granby Notch, an approximately 2.5-mile (4.0 km) square detour into Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The origin of this anomaly is clearly established in a long line of disputes and temporary agreements which were finally concluded in 1804, when southern Southwick's residents sought to leave Massachusetts, and the town was split in half.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The southwestern border of Connecticut where it abuts New York State is marked by a panhandle in Fairfield County and the Western Connecticut Planning Region, containing the towns of Greenwich, Stamford, New Canaan, Darien, and parts of Norwalk and Wilton.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Areas maintained by the National Park Service include Appalachian National Scenic Trail, Quinebaug and Shetucket Rivers Valley National Heritage Corridor, and Weir Farm National Historic Site.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut lies at the rough transition zone between the southern end of the humid continental climate and the northern portion of the humid subtropical climate.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Northern Connecticut generally experiences a climate with hot, humid summers and moderately cold winters with periodic snowfall.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Far southern and coastal Connecticut has a climate with cool winters with a mix of rain and infrequent snow, and the long hot and humid summers typical of the middle and lower East Coast.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Coastal Connecticut is the very broad transition zone between the humid continental climate and the humid subtropical climate.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut sees a fairly even precipitation pattern spread throughout the 12 months.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut averages 56% of possible sunshine (higher than the U.S. national average), averaging 2,400 hours of sunshine annually.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Occasionally, some months may see extremes in precipitation, either much higher or lower than normal, though long term droughts and floods are rare.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Early spring can range from slightly cool (40s to low 50s °F / 4.4 to 10 °C) to warm (18 to 21 °C or 65 to 70 °F), while mid and late spring (late April/May) is warm.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] By late May, the building Bermuda High creates a southerly flow of warm and humid tropical air, bringing hot weather conditions throughout the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Average highs are 81 °F (27 °C) in New London and 85 °F (29 °C) in Windsor Locks at the peak of summer in late July.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] On occasion, heat waves with highs from 90 to 100 °F (32 to 38 °C) occur across Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut's record high temperature is 106 °F (41 °C) which occurred in Danbury on July 15, 1995.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Although summers are sunny in Connecticut, quick moving summer thunderstorms can bring brief downpours with thunder and lightning.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Occasionally these thunderstorms can be severe, and the state usually averages one tornado per year.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] During hurricane season, the remains of tropical cyclones occasionally affect the region, though a direct hit is rare.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Some notable hurricanes to impact the state include the 1938 New England hurricane, Hurricane Carol in 1954, Hurricane Sandy in 2012, and Hurricane Isaias in 2020.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Weather commonly associated with the fall season typically begins in October and lasts to the first days of December.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Daily high temperatures in October and November range from the 50s to 60s °F or 10 to 15.6 °C.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Winters (December through mid-March) are moderately generally cold from south to north in Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The coldest month (January) has average high temperatures ranging from 38 °F (3 °C) in the coastal lowlands to 33 °F (1 °C) in the inland and northern portions on the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The lowest temperature recorded in Connecticut is −32 °F (−36 °C) which has been observed twice: in Falls Village on February 16, 1943, and in Coventry on January 22, 1961.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] The average yearly snowfall ranges from about 60 inches (1,500 mm) in the higher elevations of the northern portion of the state to only 20–25 inches (510–640 mm) along the southeast coast of Connecticut (Branford to Groton).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Most of Connecticut has less than 60 days of snow cover, while coastal areas often only see 30 days or so of snowcover.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Annually, 95% of seasonal snowfall in Connecticut falls from early December to late March.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] On occasion in winter, Connecticut can occasionally get heavy snowstorms, called nor'easters, which may produce as much as two feet of snow on rare occasions.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Although rare, ice storms also occur on occasion, such as the Southern New England ice storm of 1973.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Forests consist of a mix of Northeastern coastal forests of oak in southern areas of the state, to the upland New England-Acadian forests in the northwestern parts of the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Mountain Laurel (*Kalmia latifolia*) is the state flower and is native to low ridges in several parts of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Rosebay rhododendron (*Rhododendron maximum*) is also native to eastern uplands of Connecticut and Pachaug State Forest is home to the Rhododendron Sanctuary Trail.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Atlantic white cedar (*Chamaecyparis thyoides*), is found in wetlands in the southern parts of the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut has one native cactus (*Opuntia humifusa*), found in sandy coastal areas and low hillsides.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Several types of beach grasses and wildflowers are also native to Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Connecticut spans USDA Plant Hardiness Zones 5b to 7a.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p01] Coastal Connecticut is the broad transition zone where more southern and subtropical plants are cultivated.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of the 2020 United States census, Connecticut has a population of 3,605,944, an increase of 31,847 people (0.9%) from the 2010 United States census.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Among the census records, 20.4% of the population was under 18.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 1790, 97% of the population in Connecticut was classified as "rural".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The first census in which less than half the population was classified as rural was 1890.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In the 2000 census, only 12.3% was considered rural.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Most of western and southern Connecticut (particularly the Gold Coast) is strongly associated with New York City; this area is the most affluent and populous region of the state and has high property costs and high incomes.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The center of population of Connecticut is located in the town of Cheshire.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,930 homeless people in Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In common with the majority of the United States, non-Hispanic whites have remained the dominant racial and ethnic group in Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] From being 98% of the population in 1940, however, they have declined to 63% of the population as of the 2020 census.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] These statistics have represented fewer Americans identifying as non-Hispanic white, which has given rise to the Hispanic and Latino American population and Asian American population overall.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2011, 46.1% of Connecticut's population younger than age 1 were minorities.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 1870, native-born Americans had accounted for 75% of the state's population, but that had dropped to 35% by 1918.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Also as of 2000, 81.69% of Connecticut residents age 5 and older spoke English at home and 8.42% spoke Spanish, followed by Italian at 1.59%, French at 1.31%, and Polish at 1.20%.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Hispanics in Connecticut make up 19.2% of the population, predominantly of Puerto Rican (8.2%) origin, followed by Mexican (1.7%) and Dominican (1.5%).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The state has the highest share of Puerto Ricans in the country and the sixth largest Puerto Rican population (301,931) in the country.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut is one of the most racially segregated states in the nation, with the nonwhite population largely concentrated in major urban areas such as Bridgeport, Hartford, New Haven and Waterbury.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In many cases, towns neighboring urban areas are sharply segregated from them.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The top countries of origin for Connecticut's immigrants in 2018 were India, Jamaica, the Dominican Republic, Poland and Ecuador.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] A 2014 Pew survey of Connecticut residents' religious self-identification showed the following distribution of affiliations Protestant 35%, Roman Catholic 33%, non-religious 28%, Jewish 3%, Mormonism 1%, Orthodox 1%, Jehovah's Witness 1%, Hinduism 1%, Buddhism 1% and Islam 1%.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Jewish population is concentrated in the towns near Long Island Sound between Greenwich and New Haven, in Greater New Haven and in Greater Hartford, especially the suburb of West Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] According to the Association of Religion Data Archives, the largest Christian denominations, by number of adherents, in 2010 were: the Catholic Church, with 1,252,936; the United Church of Christ, with 96,506; and non-denominational Evangelical Protestants, with 72,863.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Recent immigration has brought other non-Christian religions to the state, but the numbers of adherents of other religions are still low.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut is also home to New England's largest Protestant church: The First Cathedral in Bloomfield, Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Hartford is seat to the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Hartford, which is sovereign over the Diocese of Bridgeport and the Diocese of Norwich.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] By a 2020 Public Religion Research Institute survey, 71% of the population identified as some form of Christian.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It found the state to be 21% non-religious and specifically 19% white mainline Protestant, 19% white Catholic, 9% white evangelical Protestant, 7% black Protestant, and 7% Hispanic Catholic.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In contrast to the 2014 Pew survey, the 2020 PRRI survey found Connecticut to be 40% Protestant and 28% Catholic (with the remainder of Christians being Mormon at 2%, and Orthodox at 1%).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The PRRI survey found Jewish citizens to be 2% of the population and, like the Pew survey: Hindus, Buddhists, and Muslims to be 1% each.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 2025, the gross state product for Connecticut was $376.4 billion.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut's per capita personal income in 2025 was $98,879.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] There is a large disparity in incomes throughout the state; Connecticut was tied with California and Massachusetts for the second highest (after New York's 0.52) Gini coefficient, at 0.50, as of 2020.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2025, it remained tied for second with Louisiana, with only New York having higher levels of inequality.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Despite its overall inequality, Connecticut has a relatively low poverty rate.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] According to a 2018 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Connecticut had the third-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 7.75%.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] New Canaan is the wealthiest town in Connecticut, with a per capita income of $105,846.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Hartford is the poorest municipality in Connecticut, with a per capita income of $16,798 in 2020.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] At the county level, per capita income ranged from $48,295 in Fairfield County to $26,585 in Windham County, which is close to the United States average.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of May 2025, Connecticut's unemployment rate was 3.8%, with U.S. unemployment at 4.2% that month.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Dating back to 1982, Connecticut recorded its lowest unemployment in 2000 between August and October, at 2.2%.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The highest unemployment rate during that period occurred in November and December 2010 at 9.3%, but economists expected record new levels of layoffs as a result of business closures in the spring of 2020 due to the coronavirus pandemic.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Tax is collected by the Connecticut Department of Revenue Services and by local municipalities.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2012, Connecticut residents had the second highest rate in the nation of combined state and local taxes after New York, at 12.6% of income compared to the national average of 9.9% as reported by the Tax Foundation.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Before 1991, Connecticut had an investment-only income tax system.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Income from employment was untaxed, but income from investments was taxed at 13%, the highest rate in the U.S., with no deductions allowed for costs of producing the investment income, such as interest on borrowing.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Weicker Jr., an independent, the system was changed to one in which the taxes on employment income and investment income were equalized at a maximum rate of 4%.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The new tax policy drew investment firms to Connecticut; as of 2019, Fairfield County was home to the headquarters for 16 of the 200 largest hedge funds in the world.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] All wages of Connecticut residents are subject to the state's income tax, even if earned outside the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] However, in those cases, Connecticut income tax must be withheld only to the extent the Connecticut tax exceeds the amount withheld by the other jurisdiction.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Since New York has higher income tax rates than Connecticut, this effectively means that Connecticut residents who work in New York have no Connecticut income tax withheld.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut permits a credit for taxes paid to other jurisdictions, but since residents who work in other states are still subject to Connecticut income taxation, they may owe taxes if the jurisdictional credit does not fully offset the Connecticut tax amount.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut levies a 6.35% state sales tax on the retail sale, lease, or rental of most goods.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Some items and services in general are not subject to sales and use taxes unless specifically enumerated as taxable by statute.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] A provision excluding clothing under $50 from sales tax was repealed as of July 1, 2011.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] There are no additional sales taxes imposed by local jurisdictions.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 2001, Connecticut instituted what became an annual sales tax "holiday" each August lasting one week, when retailers do not have to remit sales tax on certain items and quantities of clothing that has varied from year to year.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] State law authorizes municipalities to tax property, including real estate, vehicles and other personal property, with state statute providing varying exemptions, credits and abatements.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] All assessments are at 70% of fair market value.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The maximum property tax credit is $200 per return and any excess may not be refunded or carried forward.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] According to the Tax Foundation, on a per capita basis in the 2017 fiscal year Connecticut residents paid the 3rd highest average property taxes in the nation after New Hampshire and New Jersey.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of January 1, 2020, gasoline taxes and fees in Connecticut were 40.13 cents per gallon, 11th highest in the United States which had a nationwide average of 36.13 cents a gallon excluding federal taxes.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Diesel taxes and fees as of January 2020 in Connecticut were 46.50 cents per gallon, ninth highest nationally with the U.S. average at 37.91 cents.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 2019, sales of single-family homes in Connecticut totaled 33,146 units, a 2.1 percent decline from the 2018 transaction total.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The median home sold in 2019 recorded a transaction amount of $260,000, up 0.4 percent from 2018.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut had the seventh highest rate of home foreclosure activity in the country in 2019 at 0.53 percent of the total housing stock.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Finance, insurance and real estate was Connecticut's largest industry in 2018 as ranked by gross domestic product, generating $75.7 billion in GDP that year.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The combined educational, health and social services sector was the largest single industry as ranked by employment, with a combined workforce of 342,600 people at the end of 2019, ranking fourth the year before in GDP at $28.3 billion.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The broad business and professional services sector had the second highest GDP total in Connecticut in 2018 at an estimated $33.7 billion.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Manufacturing was the third biggest industry in 2018 with GDP of $30.8 billion, dominated by Raytheon Technologies formed in the March 2020 merger of Hartford-based United Technologies and Waltham, Mass.-based Raytheon Co.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of the merger, Raytheon Technologies employed about 19,000 people in Connecticut through subsidiaries Pratt & Whitney and Collins Aerospace.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Lockheed Martin subsidiary Sikorsky Aircraft operates Connecticut's single largest manufacturing plant in Stratford, where it makes helicopters.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Major audio equipment manufacturing company Harman International, a subsidiary of Samsung Electronics and owner of JBL, AKG and Harman Kardon, is headquartered in Stamford, Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Other major manufacturers include the Electric Boat division of General Dynamics, which makes submarines in Groton.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut historically was a center of gun manufacturing, and four gun-manufacturing firms continued to operate in the state as of December 2012, employing 2,000 people: Colt, Stag, Ruger, and Mossberg.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Marlin, owned by Remington, closed in April 2011.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Other large components of the Connecticut economy in 2018 included wholesale trade ($18.1 billion in GDP); information services ($13.8 billion); retail ($13.7 billion); arts, entertainment and food services ($9.1 billion); and construction ($8.3 billion).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Tourists spent $9.3 billion in Connecticut in 2017 according to estimates as part of a series of studies commissioned by the state of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Foxwoods Resort Casino and Mohegan Sun are the two biggest tourist draws and number among the state's largest employers; both are located on Native American reservations in the southeastern Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut's agricultural production totaled $580 million in 2017, with just over half of that revenue the result of nursery stock production.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Milk production totaled $81 million that year, with other major product categories including eggs, vegetables and fruit, tobacco and shellfish.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut's economy uses less energy to produce each dollar of GDP than all other states except California, Massachusetts, and New York.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It uses less energy on a per-capita basis than all but six other states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It has no fossil-fuel resources, but does have renewable resources.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Average retail electricity prices are the highest among the 48 contiguous states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] While most of the state's energy consumption is generated using fossil fuels, nuclear power delivered over 40% of state's electricity generation in 2019.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Refuse-derived fuels and other biomass provided the largest share of renewable electricity at about a 3% share.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Solar and wind generation have grown in recent years.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] More than three-quarters of solar generation came from distributed small-scale installations such as rooftop solar in 2019, and there is planning underway to significantly increase renewable generation with the state's offshore wind resource.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] I-95 and Route 15 were originally toll roads; they relied on a system of toll plazas at which all traffic stopped and paid fixed tolls.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] A series of major crashes at these plazas eventually contributed to the decision to remove the tolls in 1988.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Other major arteries in the state include U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Route 7 (US 7) in the west traveling parallel to the New York state line, Route 8 farther east near the industrial city of Waterbury and traveling north–south along the Naugatuck River Valley nearly parallel with US 7, and Route 9 in the east.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Between New Haven and New York City, I-95 is one of the most congested highways in the United States.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Although I-95 has been widened in several spots, some areas are only three lanes and this strains traffic capacity, resulting in frequent and lengthy rush hour delays.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Frequently, the congestion spills over to clog the parallel Merritt Parkway and even US 1.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The state has encouraged traffic reduction schemes, including rail use and ride-sharing.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut also has a very active bicycling community, with one of the highest rates of bicycle ownership and use in the United States, particularly in New Haven.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Census 2006 American Community Survey, New Haven has the highest percentage of commuters who bicycle to work of any major metropolitan center on the East Coast.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Rail is a popular travel mode between New Haven and New York City's Grand Central Terminal.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Southwestern Connecticut is served by the Metro-North Railroad's New Haven Line, operated by the Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Metro-North provides commuter service between New York City and New Haven, with branches to New Canaan, Danbury, and Waterbury.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut lies along Amtrak's Northeast Corridor, which features frequent Northeast Regional and Acela Express service from New Haven south to New York City, Philadelphia, Baltimore, Washington, D.C., and Norfolk, VA, as well as north to New London, Providence and Boston.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Since 1990, coastal cities and towns between New Haven and New London are also served by the Shore Line East commuter line.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In June 2018, a commuter rail service called the Hartford Line began operating between New Haven and Springfield on Amtrak's New Haven-Springfield Line.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Hartford Line service is provided by both Amtrak and the Connecticut Department of Transportation's CT Rail, and in addition to its termini serves New Haven State Street, Wallingford, Meriden, Berlin, Hartford, Windsor, and Windsor Locks.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Several infill stations are planned to be added in the near future as of 2021.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Amtrak's Vermonter runs from Washington to St.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In July 2019, Amtrak launched the *Valley Flyer*, which runs between New Haven and Greenfield, Massachusetts.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] A proposed commuter rail service, the Central Corridor Rail Line, would connect New London with Norwich, Willimantic, Storrs via the main campus of the University of Connecticut, and Stafford Springs, with service continuing into Massachusetts and Brattleboro, Vermont.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The proposal also adds stops to service popular tourist destinations Foxwoods Resort Casino and Mohegan Sun.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Statewide bus service is supplied by Connecticut Transit, owned by the Connecticut Department of Transportation, with smaller municipal authorities providing local service.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Bus networks are an important part of the transportation system in Connecticut, especially in urban areas like Hartford, Stamford, Norwalk, Bridgeport and New Haven.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut Transit also operates CTfastrak, a bus rapid transit service between New Britain and Hartford, which opened to the public on March 28, 2015.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut's largest airport is Bradley International Airport in Windsor Locks, 15 miles (24 km) north of Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Many residents of central and southern Connecticut also make heavy use of JFK International Airport and Newark International Airports, especially for international travel.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Smaller regional air service is provided at Tweed New Haven Regional Airport.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Larger civil airports include Danbury Municipal Airport and Waterbury-Oxford Airport in western Connecticut, Hartford–Brainard Airport in central Connecticut, and Groton-New London Airport in eastern Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Sikorsky Memorial Airport is located in Stratford and mostly services cargo, helicopter and private aviation.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Several ferry services cross Long Island Sound and connect the state to Long Island.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport & Port Jefferson Ferry travels between Bridgeport, Connecticut, and Port Jefferson, New York.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Ferry service also operates out of New London to Orient, New York; Fishers Island, New York; and Block Island, Rhode Island, which are popular tourist destinations.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Two ferries cross the Connecticut River: the Rocky Hill–Glastonbury ferry and the Chester–Hadlyme ferry, the former of which is the oldest continuously operating ferry in the United States, operating since 1655.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Hartford has been the sole capital of Connecticut since 1875.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Before then, New Haven and Hartford alternated as dual capitals.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut is known as the "Constitution State".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The origin of this nickname is uncertain, but it likely comes from Connecticut's pivotal role in the federal constitutional convention of 1787, during which Roger Sherman and Oliver Ellsworth helped to orchestrate what became known as the Connecticut Compromise, or the Great Compromise.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] This plan combined the Virginia Plan and the New Jersey Plan to form a bicameral legislature, a form copied by almost every state constitution since the adoption of the federal constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Variations of the bicameral legislature had been proposed by Virginia and New Jersey, but Connecticut's plan was the one that was in effect until the early 20th century, when Senators ceased to be selected by their state legislatures and were instead directly elected.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Otherwise, it is still the design of Congress.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The nickname also might refer to the Fundamental Orders of 1638–39.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] These Fundamental Orders represent the framework for the first formal Connecticut state government written by a representative body in Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The State of Connecticut government has operated under the direction of four separate documents in the course of the state's constitutional history.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] After the Fundamental Orders, Connecticut was granted governmental authority by King Charles II of England through the Connecticut Charter of 1662.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Separate branches of government did not exist during this period, and the General Assembly acted as the supreme authority.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] A constitution similar to the modern U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Constitution was not adopted in Connecticut until 1818.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Finally, the current state constitution was implemented in 1965.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The 1965 constitution absorbed a majority of its 1818 predecessor, but incorporated a handful of important modifications.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The governor heads the executive branch.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2020, Ned Lamont is the governor and Susan Bysiewicz is the Lieutenant Governor; both are Democrats.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] From 1639 until the adoption of the 1818 constitution, the governor presided over the General Assembly.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 1974, Ella Grasso was elected as the governor of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] This was the first time in United States history when a woman was a governor without her husband being governor first.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In addition to these departments, there are other independent bureaus, offices and commissions.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In addition to the governor and lieutenant governor, there are four other executive officers named in the state constitution that are elected directly by voters: secretary of the state, treasurer, comptroller, and attorney general.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] All executive officers are elected to four-year terms.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut's legislative branch is known as the General Assembly.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It is a bicameral legislature consisting of an upper body, the State Senate (36 senators); and a lower body, the House of Representatives (151 representatives).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Bills must pass each house in order to become law.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The governor can veto bills, but this veto can be overridden by a two-thirds majority in both houses.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Per Article XV of the state constitution, Senators and Representatives must be at least 18 years of age and are elected to two-year terms in November on even-numbered years.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] There also must always be between 30 and 50 senators and 125 to 225 representatives.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Lieutenant Governor presides over the Senate, except when absent from the chamber, when the President pro tempore presides.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Speaker of the House presides over the House.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2021, Matthew Ritter is the Speaker of the House of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2021, Connecticut's United States Senators are Richard Blumenthal (Democrat) and Chris Murphy (Democrat).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut has five representatives in the U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Locally elected representatives also develop local ordinances to govern cities and towns.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The town ordinances often include noise control and zoning guidelines.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] However, the State of Connecticut also provides statewide ordinances for noise control as well.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Connecticut Legislature has House and Senate Committees tasked with handling environmental concerns.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] These committees created the Connecticut Environmental Protection Act, passed in 1973, which gives Connecticut residents the ability to challenge and intervene when corporations propose initiatives that would cause environmental change.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] This ensures that the state will not authorize construction that would cause permanent pollution, damage, or destruction to Connecticut land.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] While Connecticut has not created many bills of its own that relate to the environment, the State follows the Clean Air Act, which is a federal law that provides air quality standards that each state needs to meet.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Act also requires the state to enact methods to improve their air quality and reduce pollutants.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut has met both Mercury and air toxicity standards, even with large power plants that release emissions.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The highest court of Connecticut's judicial branch is the Connecticut Supreme Court, headed by the Chief Justice of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Supreme Court is responsible for deciding on the constitutionality of laws, or cases as they relate to the law.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Its proceedings are similar to those of the United States Supreme Court: no testimony is given by witnesses, and the lawyers of the two sides each present oral arguments no longer than thirty minutes.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Following a court proceeding, the court may take several months to arrive at a judgment.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2020, the Chief Justice is Richard A.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 1818, the court became a separate entity, independent of the legislative and executive branches.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Connecticut Appellate Court is a lesser statewide court, and the Superior Courts are lower courts that resemble county courts of other states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut does not have county government, unlike all other states except Rhode Island.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut county governments were mostly eliminated in 1960, with the exception of sheriffs elected in each county.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 2000, the county sheriff was abolished and replaced with the state marshal system, which has districts that follow the old county territories.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The judicial system is divided into judicial districts at the trial-court level which largely follow the old county lines.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The eight counties are still widely used for purely geographical and statistical purposes, such as weather reports and census reporting, although the latter ceased to use the counties in 2024.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The state is divided into nine regional councils of government defined by the state Office of Planning and Management, which facilitate regional planning and coordination of services between member towns.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Intragovernmental Policy Division of this Office coordinates regional planning with the administrative bodies of these regions.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Each region has an administrative body made up chief executive officers of the member towns.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] By 2015, the State of Connecticut recognized COGs as county equivalents, allowing them to apply for funding and grants made available to county governments in other states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 2019 the state recommended to the United States Census Bureau that the nine Councils of Governments replace its counties for statistical purposes.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] This proposal was approved by the Census Bureau in 2022 and was fully implemented by 2024.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut shares with the rest of New England a governmental institution called the New England town.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The state is divided into 169 towns which serve as the fundamental political jurisdictions.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] There are also 21 cities, most of which simply follow the boundaries of their namesake towns and have a merged city-town government.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] There are two exceptions: the City of Groton, which is a subsection of the Town of Groton, and the City of Winsted in the Town of Winchester.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] There are also nine incorporated boroughs which may provide additional services to a section of town.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Naugatuck is a consolidated town and borough.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] For many decades, Connecticut has consistently been a blue state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] House representatives, as well as its Governor, Lt.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Governor, Attorney General, and Secretary of State, are members of the Democratic Party.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The last Republican presidential candidate to win Connecticut's votes in the Electoral College was George H.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut residents who register to vote may declare an affiliation to a political party, may become unaffiliated at will, and may change affiliations subject to certain waiting periods.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2022, around 58% of registered voters are enrolled in a political party.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Democratic Party of Connecticut is the largest party in the state by voter registration, with 36% of voters, followed by the Connecticut Republican Party with approximately 21%.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] An additional 1.6% are registered to third parties.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] As of 2022, 4 third parties have statewide enrollment privileges (meaning any state resident may register as a member), including the Libertarian Party of Connecticut, the Independent Party of Connecticut, the Connecticut Green Party, and the Connecticut Working Families Party.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut allows electoral fusion, where the same candidate can run on the ballot of more than one political party; this is often used by the Connecticut Working Families Party to cross-endorse Democratic candidates.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In July 2009, the Connecticut legislature overrode a veto by Governor M.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Jodi Rell to pass SustiNet, the first significant public-option health care reform legislation in the nation.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In April 2012, both houses of the Connecticut state legislature passed a bill (20 to 16 and 86 to 62) that abolished capital punishment for all future crimes, while 11 inmates who were waiting on the death row at the time could still be executed.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut ranked third in the nation for educational performance, according to Education Week's Quality Counts 2018 report.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It earned an overall score of 83.5 out of 100 points.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] On average, the country received a score of 75.2.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut posted a B-plus in the Chance-for-Success category, ranking fourth on factors that contribute to a person's success both within and outside the K-12 education system.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut received a mark of B-plus and finished fourth for School Finance.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It ranked 12th with a grade of C on the K-12 Achievement Index.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Hartford Public High School (1638) is the third-oldest secondary school in the nation after the Collegiate School (1628) in Manhattan and the Boston Latin School (1635).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Today, the Connecticut State Board of Education manages the public school system for children in grades K–12.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Board of Education members are appointed by the governor of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut has a number of private schools.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Private schools may file for approval by the state Department of Education, but are not required to.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Per state law, private schools must file yearly attendance reports with the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Notable private schools include Choate Rosemary Hall, The Hotchkiss School, Loomis Chaffee School, and Taft School.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut was home to the nation's first law school, Litchfield Law School, which operated from 1773 to 1833 in Litchfield.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Well known universities in the state include Yale University, Wesleyan University, Trinity College, Sacred Heart University, Fairfield University, Quinnipiac University, and the University of Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Connecticut State University System includes 4 state universities, and the state also has 12 community colleges.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The United States Coast Guard Academy is located in New London.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut has one top-flight team, the Connecticut Sun of the WNBA, who currently play at the Mohegan Sun Arena in Uncasville, but are scheduled to relocate to Houston to become the Comets in 2027.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The state has two minor league teams of American major leagues, both in Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In hockey, The Hartford Wolf Pack is an affiliate of the New York Rangers; play in the PeoplesBank Arena; and the Hartford Yard Goats of the Eastern League are a AA affiliate of the Colorado Rockies, and play at Dunkin' Park.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Norwich Sea Unicorns play in the Futures Collegiate Baseball League.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The New Britain Bees play in the Atlantic League of Professional Baseball.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut also has multiple soccer clubs: Hartford Athletic of the USL Championship plays at Trinity Health Stadium in Hartford, and CT United FC of MLS Next Pro currently plays throughout the state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The USL League Two team AC Connecticut plays in Danbury.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Pratt & Whitney Stadium has hosted both the US Men's and Women's national teams on several occasions, most recently in 2025, as well as other international friendlies.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The state hosts several major sporting events.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Since 1952, a PGA Tour golf tournament has been played in the Hartford area.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It was originally called the "Insurance City Open" and later the "Greater Hartford Open" and is now known as the Travelers Championship.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In motorsport, Lime Rock Park in Salisbury is a 1.5-mile (2.4 km) road racing course, home to the International Motor Sports Association, SCCA, United States Auto Club, and K&N Pro Series East races.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Thompson International Speedway, Stafford Motor Speedway, and Waterford Speedbowl are oval tracks holding weekly races for NASCAR Modifieds and other classes, including the NASCAR Whelen Modified Tour.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The state also hosts several major mixed martial arts events for Bellator MMA and the Ultimate Fighting Championship.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Hartford Whalers of the National Hockey League played in Hartford from 1975 to 1997 at the Hartford Civic Center.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] They departed to Raleigh, North Carolina, after disputes with the state over the construction of a new arena, and they are now known as the Carolina Hurricanes.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] A baseball team known as the Hartfords (or Hartford Dark Blues) played in the National Association from 1874 to 1875, before becoming charter members of the National League in 1876.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The team moved to Brooklyn, New York, and then disbanded one season later.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 1926, Hartford also had a franchise in the National Football League known as the Hartford Blues.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] From 2000 until 2006 the city was home to the Hartford FoxForce of World TeamTennis.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The Connecticut Huskies are the team of the University of Connecticut (UConn); they play NCAA Division I sports.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Both the men's basketball and women's basketball teams have won multiple national championships.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] In 2004, UConn became the first school in NCAA Division I history to have its men's and women's basketball programs win the national title in the same year; they repeated the feat in 2014 and are still the only Division I school to win both titles in the same year.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The UConn women's basketball team holds the record for the longest consecutive winning streak in NCAA college basketball at 111 games, a streak that ended in 2017.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Both teams play in the historic Harry A.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Gampel Pavilion and PeoplesBank Arena in Hartford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The UConn Huskies football team has played its home games at Rentschler Field in East Hartford since 2003.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] New Haven biennially hosts "The Game" between the Yale Bulldogs and the Harvard Crimson, the country's second-oldest college football rivalry.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Yale alumnus Walter Camp is deemed the "Father of American Football", and he helped develop modern football while living in New Haven.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Other Connecticut universities which feature Division I sports teams are Quinnipiac University, Fairfield University, Central Connecticut State University and Sacred Heart University.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The name "Connecticut" originated with the Mohegan word *quonehtacut*, meaning "place of long tidal river".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut's official nickname is "The Constitution State", adopted in 1959 and based on its colonial constitution of 1638–1639 which was the first in America and, arguably, the world.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut is also unofficially known as "The Nutmeg State", whose origin is unknown.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It may have come from its sailors returning from voyages with nutmeg, which was a very valuable spice in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It may have originated in the early machined sheet tin nutmeg grinders sold by early Connecticut peddlers.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] It is also facetiously said to come from Yankee peddlers from Connecticut who would sell small carved knobs of wood shaped to look like nutmeg to unsuspecting customers.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] George Washington gave Connecticut the title of "The Provisions State" because of the material aid that the state rendered to the American Revolutionary War effort.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Connecticut is also known as "The Land of Steady Habits".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] According to *Webster's New International Dictionary* (1993), a person who is a native or resident of Connecticut is a "Connecticuter".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] There are numerous other terms coined in print but not in use, such as "Connecticotian" (Cotton Mather in 1702) and "Connecticutensian" (Samuel Peters in 1781).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Linguist Allen Walker Read suggests the more playful term "Connecticutie".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] "Nutmegger" is sometimes used, as is "Yankee".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The official state song is "Yankee Doodle".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] The traditional abbreviation of the state's name is "Conn."; the official postal abbreviation is CT.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Commemorative stamps issued by the United States Postal Service with Connecticut themes include Nathan Hale, Eugene O'Neill, Josiah Willard Gibbs, Noah Webster, Eli Whitney, the whaling ship the *Charles W.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-p02] Morgan*, which is docked at Mystic Seaport, and a decoy of a broadbill duck.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] During the first twenty-four Congresses (from 1789 to 1837), Connecticut elected all its representatives in Congress from a single multi-member **Connecticut at-large congressional district**.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] Connecticut elected a varying number of representatives during this period.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] From its inception in 1789 through the first reapportionment in 1793, there were five seats.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] From 1793 through 1823, there were seven seats.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] In 1823 the seats were reduced to six and in 1837 the system of at-large members was replaced with districts.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] From 1903 to 1913 and from 1933 to 1965, Connecticut had a member of the United States House of Representatives who represented the state at-large, in addition to the members who represented distinct districts.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] All members were elected statewide at-large on a general ticket.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] but declined to serve when instead elected U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] (Pro-Administration), who had declined to serve.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] , having already been elected to the next term, see below.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] In 1837, Connecticut abandoned general tickets and adopted districts instead.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] In 1903, one at-large seat was created, four district seats continued.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district] In 1933, one at-large seat was created, five district seats continued.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Born in Newton, Massachusetts, Sherman established a legal career in Litchfield County, Connecticut, despite a lack of formal education.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] After a period in the Connecticut House of Representatives, he served as a justice of the Superior Court of Connecticut from 1766 to 1789.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Connecticut sent him to the Continental Congress, and he was a member of the Committee of Five that drafted the Declaration of Independence.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman served as a delegate to the 1787 Philadelphia Convention, which produced the United States Constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] After Benjamin Franklin, he was the second oldest delegate present at the convention.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman favored granting the federal government power to raise revenue and regulate commerce, but initially opposed efforts to supplant the Articles of Confederation with a new constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] After supporting the establishment of a new constitution, Sherman became a key delegate and main opponent of James Madison's Virginia Plan by introducing the Connecticut Compromise that won the approval of both the more and less populous states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] After the ratification of the Constitution, Sherman represented Connecticut in the United States House of Representatives from 1789 to 1791.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He served in the United States Senate from 1791 to his death in 1793.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Born in 1721, Sherman is the earliest born U.S. senator in history and was one of just three senators not to live until 1800.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was born into a family of farmers in Newton, Massachusetts.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] His parents were William and Mehetabel Sherman.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] The Shermans left Newton and settled in what became the town of Stoughton, Massachusetts, 17 miles (27 km) southeast of his home in Newton, when Roger was two.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman's education did not extend beyond his father's library and grammar school, and his early career was spent as a shoemaker.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] However, he had an aptitude for learning, access to a good library owned by his father, and a Harvard-educated parish minister, Rev.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Samuel Dunbar, who took him under his wing.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In 1743, his father's death led to Sherman moving with his mother and siblings to New Milford, Connecticut.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] There, in partnership with his brother William, he opened the town's first store, a cobbler shop.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He earned a position as the county surveyor in 1745.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] The income from this office enabled him to buy land and to earn a favorable reputation throughout the county.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman published a series of almanacs between 1750 and 1761.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He also studied law on his own, passing the bar in 1754.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He quickly introduced himself in civil and religious affairs, becoming one of the town's leading citizens and eventually town clerk of New Milford.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He became county surveyor of New Haven County in 1745 and began providing astronomical calculations for almanacs in 1759.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was married two times and had a total of 15 children, with 12 reaching adulthood.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He first married Elizabeth Hartwell on November 17, 1749, and they had six children: John, William, Isaac, Chloe (1st), Chloe (2nd), Elizabeth.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Elizabeth died in New Milford, Connecticut, on October 19, 1760.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Rebecca died in New Haven, Connecticut on April 19, 1813.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was a 5th cousin three times removed of Union general William Tecumseh Sherman.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was appointed justice of the peace in 1762 and judge of the court of common pleas in 1765.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] During 1766, Sherman was first elected to the Governor's Council of the Connecticut General Assembly, where he served until 1785.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] From 1784 to 1785, he also served as a judge of the Connecticut Supreme Court of Errors.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman served as Justice of the Superior Court of Connecticut from 1766 to 1789.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was also appointed treasurer of Yale College, and awarded an honorary Master of Arts degree.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He was a professor of religion for many years, and engaged in lengthy correspondences with some of the theologians of the time.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] During February 1776, Sherman, George Wythe, and John Adams were members of a committee responsible for establishing guidelines for U.S.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Embassy officials in Canada with the committee instructions that included, "You are to declare that we hold sacred the rights of conscience, and may promise to the whole people, solemnly in our name, the free and undisturbed exercise of their religion.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] And ... that all civil rights and the rights to hold office were to be extended to persons of any Christian denomination." In 1784, Sherman was elected mayor of New Haven, which office he held until his death.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] As a member of the First Continental Congress, Sherman signed the Continental Association to impose an economic boycott on all British trade.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In the Second Continental Congress, Sherman was appointed to the Committee of Five that drafted the Declaration of Independence.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was also a member of the committee of 13 that was responsible for preparing a draft constitution for the new nation.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] During debate, Sherman proposed a bicameral national legislature where states would be represented equally.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] The committee of 13 rejected Sherman's proposal, adopting a unicameral legislature and what would become the Articles of Confederation.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] As a member of the Confederation Congress, Sherman was a signatory of the Treaty of Paris which ended the Revolutionary War.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman came into the Convention without the intention of creating a new constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He saw the convention as a means to modify the already existing government.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Part of his stance was concerned with the public appeal.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He defended amending the articles declaring that it was in the best interest of the people and the most probable way the people would accept changes to a constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] "The problem with the old government was not that it had acted foolishly or threatened anybody's liberties, but that it had simply been unable to enforce its decrees." Sherman advanced the idea that the national government simply needed a way to raise revenue and regulate commerce.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman's views were heavily shaped by Connecticut's position as a particularly isolationist state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] His views were also influenced by his personal beliefs and Puritan views.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman opposed slavery and used the issue as a tool for negotiation and alliance.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He believed that slavery was already gradually being abolished and the trend was moving southward.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman saw that the issue of slavery could be one that threatened the success of the Constitutional Convention.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Therefore, Sherman helped shape compromises that benefited the slave states in order to obtain unlikely allies from the Carolinas due to the economies of their home states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman is also known for his stance against paper money with his authoring of Article I, Section 10 of the United States Constitution and his later opposition to James Madison over the Bill of Rights.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He believed that these amendments would diminish the role and power of the states over the people.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman also had very little interest in creating an executive branch with much authority.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He suggested that no constitutional provision needed be made for the executive because it was "nothing more than an institution for carrying the will of the Legislature into effect".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Had Sherman's views prevailed, the United States would have become a parliamentary republic with an executive presidency, where the president is elected by the legislature and must maintain its confidence to remain in office.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman also made the vice president an ex officio member of the Senate.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] They may break ties in the Senate, by having a casting vote, if the votes for passage and rejection are equally divided.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Two proposed options for the formation of the legislative branch emerged in the deliberations.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] One was to form a bicameral legislature in which both chambers had representation proportional to the population of the states, which was supported by the Virginia Plan.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] The second was to modify the unicameral legislature that had equal representation from all of the states, which was supported by the New Jersey Plan introduced by William Paterson that Sherman helped author.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He defended the unicameral legislature of the Articles of Confederation by stating that the more populous states had not "suffered at the hands of less populous states on account of the rule of equal voting".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman, Elbridge Gerry and others were of the shared opinion that the elected composition of the national government should be reserved for the vote of state officials and not for election by the will of the people.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was wary of allowing ordinary citizen participation in national government and stated that the people "should have as little to do as may be about the Government.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] They want information and are constantly liable to be misled".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] While Sherman was a devout supporter of a unicameral legislature, he recognized that this goal was unattainable because it would not receive the support of the more populous states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] With the aid of Oliver Ellsworth, Sherman repeatedly proposed a bicameral compromise where one house had representation proportional to the population, and the other had equal representation for the states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Some scholars have identified Sherman as a pivotal delegate at the Convention because of his role in settling the debate over representation.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] At important moments in the deliberations, Sherman consistently pushed the interests of the less populous states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] The states would be represented in another house called the Senate (the upper house).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In the lower house, each state had a representative for every one delegate.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In the upper house, each state was guaranteed two senators, regardless of its size.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In terms of modes of election, Sherman supported allowing each state legislature to elect its own senators.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In the House, Sherman originally proposed that the suffrage of the House should be figured according to the "numbers of free inhabitants" in each state.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was elected as a United States representative in the First Congress, and then to the Senate in the Second and Third Congresses until his death in 1793.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In 1790 both Sherman and Richard Law were appointed to revise the confused and archaic Connecticut statutes, which they accomplished.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Throughout his life, Sherman was a major benefactor of Yale College, acting as the university's treasurer for many years and promoting construction of a college chapel.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman opposed appointment of fellow signer Gouverneur Morris as minister to France because he considered that high-living patriot to be of an "irreligious nature".
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman died in his sleep on July 23, 1793, after a two-month illness diagnosed as typhoid fever.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] The *Gazette of the United States* (Philadelphia), August 17, 1793, p.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] 508, reported an alternate diagnosis, "He was taken ill about the middle of May last, and from that time declined till his death.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] His physician supposed his disorder to be seated in his liver." He was buried in New Haven Green.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] In 1821, when that cemetery was relocated, his remains were moved to the Grove Street Cemetery.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Jonathan Edwards Jr. gave a funeral sermon at the ceremony for Sherman on July 25, 1793.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He praised his contributions to his friends, family, town, and country, noting Sherman's piety and excellence in study.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman is especially notable in United States history for being the only person to sign all four great state papers of the United States: the Articles of Association, the United States Declaration of Independence, the Articles of Confederation, and the United States Constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Robert Morris, who did not sign the Articles of Association, signed the other three.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] John Dickinson also signed three: the Continental Association, the Articles of Confederation, and the United States Constitution.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He was involved with the Declaration of Independence but abstained, hoping for a reconciliation with Britain.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman is one of the most influential members of the Constitutional Convention.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] He is not well known for his actions at the Convention because he was a "terse, ineloquent speaker" who never kept a personal record of his experience, unlike other prominent figures.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] At 66 years of age, Sherman was the second eldest member at the convention following Benjamin Franklin (who was 81 years old at the time).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Yet he was a critical opponent of James Madison and the more populous states.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] Sherman was also one of the most active members of the convention; he made motions or seconds 160 times (compared to Madison's 177 times).
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] The town of Sherman, Connecticut, was named for Roger Sherman.
[src:1791-connecticut-s-at-large-congressional-district-special-election/roger-sherman] As a member of the Committee of Five, Sherman is portrayed on the pediment of the Jefferson Memorial.
